{#- GROSS-VS-NET TABLE â€” vs-tableâ†’.cmp. Carries the gross-vs-net body prose. -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="acctind-agency-comparison">
  <div class="ct">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">Â§</span><span class="idx__t">The most consequential accounting decision an agency makes</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:10px;">Gross revenue presentation vs. net revenue presentation.</h2>
    <p class="lede" style="margin:0 0 24px;max-width:72ch;">For media-heavy and production-heavy agencies, the gross-vs-net question changes apparent revenue by 5&ndash;10&times; and every margin metric with it. Here&rsquo;s what the same agency looks like under each presentation &mdash; and why most agencies should be on net.</p>
    <table class="cmp">
      <caption class="sr-only">Gross vs. net revenue presentation for agencies</caption>
      <thead><tr><th scope="col">Same agency, two presentations</th><th scope="col">Gross (agency-as-principal)</th><th scope="col" class="num us">Net (agency-as-agent &mdash; most common)</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><th scope="row" data-col="Same agency, two presentations">Example: $1M media + $150K fee</th><td data-col="Gross (agency-as-principal)">Revenue $1,150,000 &middot; COGS $1,000,000 &middot; Gross profit $150,000</td><td class="num us" data-col="Net (agency-as-agent)">Revenue $150,000 &middot; no pass-through in revenue or COGS &middot; Gross profit $150,000</td></tr>
        <tr><th scope="row" data-col="Same agency, two presentations">ASC 606 framework</th><td data-col="Gross (agency-as-principal)">Agency controls media before transfer; takes inventory risk; full pricing discretion</td><td class="num us" data-col="Net (agency-as-agent)">Agency arranges for media; supplier controls until placed; limited or no inventory risk</td></tr>
        <tr><th scope="row" data-col="Same agency, two presentations">Apparent revenue</th><td data-col="Gross (agency-as-principal)">Inflated 5&ndash;10&times; for media-heavy agencies</td><td class="num us" data-col="Net (agency-as-agent)">Reflects actual economic earnings &mdash; matches AGI</td></tr>
        <tr><th scope="row" data-col="Same agency, two presentations">Gross margin %</th><td data-col="Gross (agency-as-principal)">Distorted: 13% on $1.15M of &ldquo;revenue&rdquo;</td><td class="num us" data-col="Net (agency-as-agent)">100% on $150K of true revenue</td></tr>
        <tr><th scope="row" data-col="Same agency, two presentations">Industry benchmarking</th><td data-col="Gross (agency-as-principal)">Incompatible with industry data (Adweek, AdAge, 4A&rsquo;s, RECMA all report AGI)</td><td class="num us" data-col="Net (agency-as-agent)">Matches industry-standard reporting; benchmarks become usable</td></tr>
        <tr><th scope="row" data-col="Same agency, two presentations">Fundraise / M&amp;A diligence</th><td data-col="Gross (agency-as-principal)">Buyer or investor immediately restates to net; trust eroded</td><td class="num us" data-col="Net (agency-as-agent)">Survives diligence cleanly; an agency-sophistication signal</td></tr>
        <tr><th scope="row" data-col="Same agency, two presentations">When gross is actually correct</th><td data-col="Gross (agency-as-principal)">Agency holds inventory, sets retail price, takes the loss if unsold</td><td class="num us" data-col="Net (agency-as-agent)">Most agency engagements fail the principal test; net is the default</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p class="prose" style="font-size:13.5px;color:var(--color-ink-mute);margin-top:14px;">The principal-vs-agent analysis is performed engagement by engagement under ASC 606, not at the agency level &mdash; an agency may operate as principal on some work (production-buyout deals where it owns the deliverable) and agent on others (media buys, talent fees, third-party software resale). The chart of accounts handles both cleanly with clear separation.</p>
  </div>
</section>

